('business:5-1-role-of-finance-function:match:7f0dfc79', 'business', 'business:5-1-role-of-finance-function', '5.1 Role of Finance Function', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Average Rate of Return”?", "options": ["When a limited company raises finance by selling ownership stakes (shares) to investors.", "A measure of how profitable an investment is, calculated as the average annual profit as a percentage of the amount invested.", "The department within a larger business that manages money, produces financial information, and supports decision-making.", "The money a business receives from selling its goods or services."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "“Average Rate of Return” means: A measure of how profitable an investment is, calculated as the average annual profit as a percentage of the amount invested."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-1-role-of-finance-function:match:aab58e8a', 'business', 'business:5-1-role-of-finance-function', '5.1 Role of Finance Function', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Share Issue”?", "options": ["The department within a larger business that manages money, produces financial information, and supports decision-making.", "When a limited company raises finance by selling ownership stakes (shares) to investors.", "The money a business receives from selling its goods or services.", "The expenses involved in making and selling a product or service."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "“Share Issue” means: When a limited company raises finance by selling ownership stakes (shares) to investors."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:exam:acab02f7', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "Which of the following is least likely to be a reason for a business to need finance?", "options": ["To decrease the size of the workforce", "To extend a marketing campaign", "To increase the size of its factory", "To reduce the amount of stock it purchases"], "hint": "Think about which option actually reduces spending rather than requiring money to be spent.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D — To reduce the amount of stock it purchases</h5><p><strong>Why D is correct:</strong> Reducing stock purchases means the business is spending less money, so it needs less finance — not more.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Decrease the workforce:</strong> Making staff redundant requires redundancy payments, which need financing.</li><li><strong>B — Extend a marketing campaign:</strong> Marketing costs money — advertising, promotions and campaigns all require finance.</li><li><strong>C — Increase factory size:</strong> Expanding premises is a major capital expenditure that requires significant long-term finance.</li></ul><p><strong>Examiner''s Comment:</strong> Under half of students answered correctly. Many chose A, suggesting they didn''t realise that redundancy payments require finance.</p></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:exam:e921db70', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q3", "question": "Which of the following is an advantage of receiving trade credit?", "options": ["It can be used to pay wages and salaries", "It encourages production operatives to work harder", "It is often interest free", "It may bring new skills into the business"], "hint": "What is the key feature of trade credit that makes it attractive to businesses managing their cash flow?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — It is often interest free</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Trade credit is typically interest-free within the agreed repayment period (e.g. 30–90 days), which makes it an attractive, cost-free way to manage cash flow when buying stock.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Pay wages and salaries:</strong> Trade credit is specifically for purchasing goods from suppliers — it cannot be used to pay wages.</li><li><strong>B — Encourages workers to work harder:</strong> This is entirely unrelated to trade credit, which is a financial arrangement between businesses, not employees.</li><li><strong>D — Brings new skills into the business:</strong> This is a benefit of taking on a new partner, not trade credit.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:exam:73f5361d', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "Which of the following is a benefit to a public limited company of using a share issue to raise finance?", "options": ["Dividends will need to be paid", "New skills will be brought into the company", "No interest will be paid", "Repayments will be spread over a long period of time"], "hint": "Think about the key financial advantage of a share issue compared to a bank loan. What cost does a share issue avoid?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — No interest will be paid</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Unlike a bank loan or overdraft, a share issue does not require the business to pay interest. The money raised does not need to be repaid, and there is no interest charge.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Dividends will need to be paid:</strong> This is a disadvantage of a share issue, not a benefit. Dividends are a cost to the business.</li><li><strong>B — New skills will be brought into the company:</strong> This can happen but is not guaranteed — it is a possible benefit of new shareholders, not a definitive advantage of the share issue itself.</li><li><strong>D — Repayments spread over a long period:</strong> This describes a bank loan, not a share issue. Share capital does not require repayment at all.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:exam:2fa383c1', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q7", "question": "Which of the following is a short-term source of finance suitable for a new business?", "options": ["Retained profit", "Sale of business assets", "Share issue", "Trade credit"], "hint": "Which option is available to a brand new business with no previous trading history? Which one is also short-term?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D — Trade credit</h5><p><strong>Why D is correct:</strong> Trade credit allows a new business to obtain goods from suppliers and pay later (usually 30–90 days). It is short-term and available to new businesses from the start.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Retained profit:</strong> Only available to established businesses that have already made and kept profit. A new business has no retained profit.</li><li><strong>B — Sale of business assets:</strong> A new business has no assets to sell. This is only available to established businesses.</li><li><strong>C — Share issue:</strong> This is a long-term source of finance for limited companies only — not typically short-term, and requires the business to be incorporated.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:exam:0f8ca026', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "A business has decided to update all of its computers and printers. This decision will:", "options": ["Increase selling prices", "Reduce fixed costs", "Require financial resources", "Temporarily increase cash inflows"], "hint": "What does buying new equipment mean for the business in financial terms?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — Require financial resources</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Updating equipment is a capital expenditure — it requires money (financial resources) to purchase the computers and printers.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Increase selling prices:</strong> Buying new computers does not automatically allow a business to charge more for its products or services.</li><li><strong>B — Reduce fixed costs:</strong> New equipment may eventually reduce costs (e.g. through efficiency), but initially it increases costs, not reduces them.</li><li><strong>D — Temporarily increase cash inflows:</strong> Buying equipment is a cash outflow, not an inflow. It takes money out of the business.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:exam:a72bf5c0', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q10", "question": "Which of the following is an appropriate source of finance for a newly established company?", "options": ["Overdraft", "Retained profit", "Sale of assets", "Taking a partner"], "hint": "Which of these is available to a business that has only just started trading and has no financial history?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: A — Overdraft</h5><p><strong>Why A is correct:</strong> An overdraft can be arranged with a bank by a new business to help cover short-term cash flow needs. It is one of the few external sources accessible from the start.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>B — Retained profit:</strong> A newly established company has not yet made any profit, so there is nothing to retain and reinvest.</li><li><strong>C — Sale of assets:</strong> A new business typically has very few or no assets to sell.</li><li><strong>D — Taking a partner:</strong> While possible, this is less typical for a newly established company and is more of a structural decision than a routine source of start-up finance.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:exam:9553ae92', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q12", "question": "A sole trader is short of cash to pay a supplier this month. She should:", "options": ["Buy higher quality products", "Improve customer service", "Get an overdraft", "Repay her loan"], "hint": "What short-term financial tool allows a business to spend more than it has in its account to cover immediate payments?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — Get an overdraft</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> An overdraft is specifically designed for short-term cash flow problems. It allows a business to spend more than its current bank balance, covering immediate payments such as a supplier invoice.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Buy higher quality products:</strong> This would cost more money, making the cash shortage worse — not better.</li><li><strong>B — Improve customer service:</strong> While beneficial long-term, improving customer service does not solve an immediate cash shortage this month.</li><li><strong>D — Repay her loan:</strong> Repaying a loan would further reduce the cash available, making it even harder to pay the supplier.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:mcq:ae610bd9', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is a short-term, external source of finance?", "options": ["Retained profit", "Owner''s capital", "Overdraft", "Sale of assets"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: C — Overdraft. An overdraft is arranged with a bank and allows a business to spend more than its account balance. It is external (from a bank) and short-term (used for day-to-day cash needs). Retained profit and owner''s capital are internal sources. Sale of assets can be internal but is not specifically short-term."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:mcq:30c2abf8', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is NOT a feature of trade credit?", "options": ["The supplier does not need to be paid for 90 days", "Interest has to be paid if the money is not paid within the time limit", "It is useful for dealing with a short-term cash flow problem", "It can be used to finance the purchase of new machinery"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Correct answer: D. Trade credit is a short-term source used to buy stock or raw materials — it is not suitable for financing the purchase of capital assets such as new machinery, which requires medium- or long-term finance."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:mcq:92da3e22', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following involves money being reinvested by the business?", "options": ["Overdraft", "Bank loan", "Retained profit", "Crowdfunding"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: C — Retained profit. This is profit earned by the business that is not paid out to owners but reinvested back into the business. Overdraft and bank loans are external borrowing. Crowdfunding raises money from external contributors."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:mcq:310b664c', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A sole trader borrows £12,000 at 8% interest per year. How much interest will she pay in the first year?", "options": ["£430", "£960", "£1200", "£1500"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct answer: B — £960. The calculation is £12,000 × 0.08 = £960. A is incorrect (£430 has no basis). C would be 10% interest. D would be 12.5% interest."}'::jsonb),
('business:5-2-sources-of-finance:mcq:acab02f7', 'business', 'business:5-2-sources-of-finance', '5.2 Sources of Finance', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is least likely to be a reason for a business to need finance?", "options": ["To decrease the size of the workforce", "To extend a marketing campaign", "To increase the size of its factory", "To reduce the amount of stock it purchases"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Correct answer: D. Reducing stock purchases actually decreases the need for finance. Extending a marketing campaign (B), increasing factory size (C), and even decreasing the workforce (A — redundancy payments are required) all require spending money."}'::jsonb)
